{"parse":{"title":"Long-stitch bookbinding","pageid":9231628,"revid":784166294,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><table role=\"presentation\" class=\"mbox-small plainlinks sistersitebox\" style=\"background-color:#f9f9f9;border:1px solid #aaa;color:#000\">\n<tbody><tr>\n<td class=\"mbox-image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/df/Wikibooks-logo-en-noslogan.svg/40px-Wikibooks-logo-en-noslogan.svg.png\" width=\"40\" height=\"40\" class=\"noviewer\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/df/Wikibooks-logo-en-noslogan.svg/60px-Wikibooks-logo-en-noslogan.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/df/Wikibooks-logo-en-noslogan.svg/80px-Wikibooks-logo-en-noslogan.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"400\" data-file-height=\"400\" /></td>\n<td class=\"mbox-text plainlist\">The Wikibook <i><a href=\"https://en.wikibooks.org/wiki/Bookbinding\" class=\"extiw\" title=\"wikibooks:Bookbinding\">Bookbinding</a></i> has a page on the topic of: <i><b><a href=\"https://en.wikibooks.org/wiki/Bookbinding/Long_stitch\" class=\"extiw\" title=\"wikibooks:Bookbinding/Long stitch\">Long stitch</a></b></i></td></tr></tbody></table>\n<table class=\"plainlinks metadata ambox ambox-content ambox-one_source\" role=\"presentation\"><tbody><tr><td class=\"mbox-image\"><div style=\"width:52px\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Question_book-new.svg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Question book-new.svg\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/50px-Question_book-new.svg.png\" width=\"50\" height=\"39\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/75px-Question_book-new.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/100px-Question_book-new.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"512\" data-file-height=\"399\" /></a></div></td><td class=\"mbox-text\"><div class=\"mbox-text-span\">This article <b>relies largely or entirely on a single <a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Identifying_reliable_sources\" title=\"Wikipedia:Identifying reliable sources\">source</a></b>.<span class=\"hide-when-compact\"> Relevant discussion may be found on the <a href=\"/wiki/Talk:Long-stitch_bookbinding##\" title=\"Talk:Long-stitch bookbinding\">talk page</a>. Please help <a class=\"external text\" href=\"//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Long-stitch_bookbinding&amp;action=edit\">improve this article</a> by introducing <a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Citing_sources\" title=\"Wikipedia:Citing sources\">citations</a> to additional sources.</span>  <small><i>(May 2013)</i></small></div></td></tr></tbody></table>\n<p><b>Longstitch</b> is a <a href=\"/wiki/Bookbinding\" title=\"Bookbinding\">bookbinding</a> technique used for sewing together the sections of a book. There are different forms of longstitch sewings.  Longstitch binding does not require glue, though there are methods that utilize glue. In his book <i>Non Adhesive Bindings,</i> <a href=\"/wiki/Keith_A._Smith\" title=\"Keith A. Smith\">Keith Smith</a> describes the \"Longstitch through a slotted cover\" and it involves sewing each section directly through the cover where slots have been made at each sewing station.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> This sewing method creates a staggered line pattern visible on the spine. Keith Smith indicates that this type of longstitch was used as early as the 18th century in some parts of Europe, and possibly earlier.\n</p>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Longstitchthroughslottedcover.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/4/40/Longstitchthroughslottedcover.jpg/220px-Longstitchthroughslottedcover.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"220\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/4/40/Longstitchthroughslottedcover.jpg/330px-Longstitchthroughslottedcover.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/4/40/Longstitchthroughslottedcover.jpg/440px-Longstitchthroughslottedcover.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"800\" data-file-height=\"800\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Longstitchthroughslottedcover.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>Sample Longstitch binding through a slotted cover</div></div></div>\n<p>Another longstitch technique is done in conjunction with a <a href=\"/wiki/Chain_stitch\" title=\"Chain stitch\">chain stitch</a>. This particular sewing method is very old and originated in Germany as early as the medieval era. In Szirmai's text, <i>The Archaeology of medieval bookbinding</i>, the author describes this method of bookbinding being used on parchment-covered books with reinforced spines between 1375 and 1500.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> The sections were sewn directly through holes in the cover material, with two sections being sewn through each row of holes. This allowed the creation of a chain stitch at the first and last sewing stations.\n</p>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Medievallongstitchbinding.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/2/2f/Medievallongstitchbinding.jpg/220px-Medievallongstitchbinding.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"207\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/2/2f/Medievallongstitchbinding.jpg/330px-Medievallongstitchbinding.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/2/2f/Medievallongstitchbinding.jpg/440px-Medievallongstitchbinding.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"800\" data-file-height=\"754\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Medievallongstitchbinding.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>Sample binding using Longstitch and Chain Stitch combination</div></div></div>\n<p>There are many ways to elaborate on the simple longstitch binding. Besides altering the stitching pattern to include crosses, altering the length of the longstitches to have their own patterns, and other patterns, artists have also used multiple colored <a href=\"/wiki/Thread_(yarn)\" title=\"Thread (yarn)\">thread</a>. There are also a number of different ways to close a longstitch book. Though some longstitch bound book covers are just <a href=\"/wiki/Book_trimming\" title=\"Book trimming\">trimmed</a> to the edge of the book block, there are a variety of ways to fold over one side of the cover and fasten it. Buttons can be stitched into the binding and a thread attached to the cover flap. A slit can also be cut into the front cover and a strip from the back cover can be slipped through the slit. Modern book artists have elaborated on closure styles.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Long-stitch_bookbinding&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Smith, Keith A. (1999). \"Non Adhesive Binding, Books Without Paste or Glue.\"<i>Sigma Foundation.</i></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Szirmai, J.A. (1999). \"The Archaeology of Medieval Bookbinding.\" <i>Scolar Pr.</i></span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Further_reading\">Further reading</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Long-stitch_bookbinding&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Further reading\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li>Smith, Keith A. (1995). \"Non Adhesive Binding, Vol. 1, Books Without Paste or Glue.\"<i>keith a smith BOOKS (Rochester, NY).</i></li>\n<li>Smith, Keith A. (1995). \"Non Adhesive Binding, Vol. 2, 1- 2- and 3-Section Sewings.\"<i>keith a smith BOOKS (Rochester, NY).</i></li>\n<li>Smith, Keith A. (1995). \"Non Adhesive Binding, Vol. 3, Exposed Spine Sewings.\"<i>keith a smith BOOKS (Rochester, NY).</i></li>\n<li>Smith, Keith A. (2001). \"Non Adhesive Binding, Vol. 4, Smith's Sewing Single Sheets.\"<i>keith a smith BOOKS (Rochester, NY).</i></li>\n<li>Smith, Keith A. (2003). \"Quick Leather Bindings, Non Adhesive Binding, Volume 5.\"<i>keith a smith BOOKS (Rochester, NY).</i></li></ul>\n<table class=\"metadata plainlinks stub\" role=\"presentation\" style=\"background:transparent\"><tbody><tr><td><a href=\"/wiki/File:Monobook_icon.svg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Stub icon\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/47/Monobook_icon.svg/30px-Monobook_icon.svg.png\" width=\"30\" height=\"30\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/47/Monobook_icon.svg/45px-Monobook_icon.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/47/Monobook_icon.svg/60px-Monobook_icon.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"128\" data-file-height=\"128\" /></a></td><td><i>This article about <a href=\"/wiki/Artists%27_books\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Artists&#39; books\">making art out of books</a>, the arts related to <a href=\"/wiki/Bookbinding\" title=\"Bookbinding\">bookbinding</a>, or <a href=\"/wiki/Book_design\" title=\"Book design\">the design of mass-produced books</a> is a <a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Stub\" title=\"Wikipedia:Stub\">stub</a>. You can help Wikipedia by <a class=\"external text\" href=\"//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Long-stitch_bookbindin